<section xml:id="negation">
  <title>Negation</title>
  <p>
    The <term>negation</term> of a statement <m>A</m>
    (which we denote <m>\overline{A}</m> or <m>\neg A</m>)
    is the statement
    <q><m>A</m> is false.</q>
    For example, the negation of the statement
    <q><m>57</m> is prime</q>
    is
    <q><m>57</m> is not prime.</q>
    The negation of the statement
    <q><m>57</m> is not prime</q>
    is
    <q><m>57</m> is prime.</q>
    Depending on the statement,
    its negation can be written differently from just inserting a
    <q>not</q>:
    <ol label="labelalph">
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>S</m> is a set,
          and <m>s</m> is not an element of <m>S</m>, then the sentence
          <q><m>s \notin S</m></q>
          is the negation of the sentence
          <q><m>s \in S</m>.</q>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>B</m> is the statement
          <q><m>x = y</m>,</q>
          then the negation <m>\overline{B}</m> is the sentence
          <q><m>x \neq y</m>.</q>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>C=``a=b''</m>, then <m>\bar{C}=``a\neq b''</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    The negation of a statement has the opposite truth value:
    if <m>A</m> is true, then <m>\overline{A}</m> is false;
    if <m>A</m> is false, then <m>\overline{A}</m> is true.
  </p>
  <tabular>
    <row>
      <cell><m>A</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\overline{A}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
      <cell></cell>
      <cell></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>T</cell>
      <cell>F</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>F</cell>
      <cell>T</cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any statement <m>A</m>, consider the statement <m>A \vee \overline{A}</m>.
        That's the statement that either <m>A</m> is true or <m>A</m> is not true.
        In other words,
        it's the assertion that either <m>A</m> is true or false.
        Here's the truth table:
      </p>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>A</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\overline{A}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>A \vee \overline{A}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>T</cell>
          <cell>F</cell>
          <cell>T</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>F</cell>
          <cell>T</cell>
          <cell>T</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
      <p>
        Note that we only have T's in the last column.
        That means that the sentence <m>A \vee \overline{A}</m> is always true,
        no matter what the truth-value of <m>A</m> is.
        This statement is sometimes called the
        <term>Law of Excluded Middle</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Now let's contemplate the statement <m>A \wedge \overline{A}</m>.
        Here's the truth table:
      </p>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>A</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\overline{A}</m></cell>
          <cell><m>A \vee \overline{A}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>T</cell>
          <cell>F</cell>
          <cell>F</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>F</cell>
          <cell>T</cell>
          <cell>F</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
      <p>
        Note that we only have F's in the last column.
        That means that <m>A \wedge \overline{A}</m> is always false,
        no matter what the truth-value of <m>A</m> is.
        This statement is sometimes just called a
        <term>Contradiction</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>